posts.description:
With Russia constantly in the news, here is a photograph from a story named “The Putin Generation” in the December issue of National Geographic Magazine. It examined the attitudes and outlooks of young people in Russia, now in their mid-twenties, who were barely ten years old when Putin first became President.

Supporters of the Other Russia, an extremist opposition party, rally in Moscow, displaying flags and armbands with their symbol, a hand grenade. The Other Russia was formed by members of the banned ultranationalist National Bolshevik Party, originally founded by poet Eduard Limonov, but it is not recognized by Putin’s government.

@natgeo @thephotosociety @natgeocreative #Russia #Moscow #youth #flags #rally #red #politics #OtherRussia

Here, @kirbase perches on a cornice in Moscow as his friend @balashovenator gets the shot. The 24-year-olds are prominent members of the city's death-defying "roofer" community, also called skywalkers. They scale Russia’s highest buildings, without safety gear, often entering illegally, bypassing security and using whatever tools necessary to reach their destinations.  Defiance of authority and the rule of law is in the roofers’ blood and that is why they have fallen under the system’s watch wrote the Moscow Times.

This photograph opens the gallery of the “Best Photos of 2016” which @natgeo just published. The images were selected from 107 stories by 91 photographers and out of over two million photographs. The photograph here was the opening image of my recent story, The Putin Generation, which ran in the December issue of the National Geographic Magazine. The story examines the attitudes and outlooks of young people, now in their mid-twenties, who were barely ten years old when Putin first became President. 
